<subSubSection id="C36265517A50FFD6FFCBFCD6FE4FFBA2" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC736DA7A50FFD6FFCBFCD6FE4FFBA2" blockId="19.[96,745,788,1032]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
The courtship display of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C784D597A50FFD6FE79FCD7FDFDFC87" authorityName="Otto &amp; Hill" authorityYear="2018" box="[466,575,788,813]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tortus">
<emphasis id="B90CEAC87A50FFD6FE79FCD7FDFDFC87" box="[466,575,788,813]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">M. tortus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
male is very unusual in that only one ornamented side of the fan is displayed to a female at a time, even when the fan is held at the center as shown here. Rotation of the fan, twisted (hence the name 
<taxonomicName id="4C784D597A50FFD6FE87FC52FEADFC00" authorityName="Otto &amp; Hill" authorityYear="2018" box="[300,367,913,938]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tortus">
<emphasis id="B90CEAC87A50FFD6FE87FC52FEADFC00" box="[300,367,913,938]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">tortus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) from one side to the other and then back again, is complicated but follows a regular pattern that is described in detail with the published description of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
